<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO DOC DEL</font><br>
<tt>Thu May 15  6:46:41 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc Del,<br><br>
You have made some good points here.<br><br>
I never got involved in jousting with Doc Spatz in the US -Vietnamese thread. I am very familiar with those who have beliefs about multiculturalism being a threat to a One Nation concept. I, personally, don't see things that way. Yet, I don't view those who envision a more &quot;homogenized&quot; society as being racist.<br><br>
Some of my first posts on Usenet were debates with a person who was overtly racist. His views were *exclusive* white supremicist views. There is a big difference in what he was espousing and what Spatz was saying.<br><br>
My impression (no, I'm not going to look up everything that was said) is that Doc Spatz was guilty of &quot;over explaining&quot; his position. He tends to do this.<br><br>
What I have come to appreciate about him is his knack for seeing the shortcoming in a particular position, which he follows with an admission of such. This is rare in our society - admitting a mistake. He has taken it upon himself to go out into the Vietnamese section of his town and seek out *individuals*. To me this represents growth and promise.<br><br>
You have made a good point about those who died and were wounded in RVN being a consideration in the decision making process of future battles. But, I must be cynical about<br>
this. <br><br>
Before the Battle of Cold Harbor, Va., the Union soldiers, after being notified of an impending frontal assault on Confederate positions, pinned notes which identified them onto their uniforms. In a matter of minutes thousands lay slaughtered. Their willingness to die did nothing to cause future leaders to consider &quot;husbanding&quot; their manpower.<br><br>
My willingness to go to Vietnam made it easy for leaders of that time. We were just as expendable as we were during the time of the Civil War. <br><br>
In Desert Storm our leader's FIRST consideration was political fallout arising as a result of protests bringing to light an abuse of our soldiers. A new counterculture is what they most feared. This led to their prudent decision to bomb, repeatedly, anything that could pose a threat to infantry and armor.<br>

<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


